Output:  <|begin_of_text|>Title: Normans

Background: Robert Guiscard, an other Norman adventurer previously elevated to the dignity of count of Apulia as the result of his military successes, ultimately drove the Byzantines out of southern Italy. Having obtained the consent of pope Gregory VII and acting as his vassal, Robert continued his campaign conquering the Balkan peninsula as a foothold for western feudal lords and the Catholic Church. After allying himself with Croatia and the Catholic cities of Dalmatia, in 1081 he led an army of 30,000 men in 300 ships landing on the southern shores of Albania, capturing Valona, Kanina, Jericho (Orikumi), and reaching Butrint after numerous pillages. They joined the fleet that had previously conquered Corfu and attacked Dyrrachium from land and sea, devastating everything along the way. Under these harsh circumstances, the locals accepted the call of emperor Alexius I Comnenus to join forces with the Byzantines against the Normans. The Albanian forces could not take part in the ensuing battle because it had started before their arrival. Immediately before the battle, the Venetian fleet had secured a victory in the coast surrounding the city. Forced to retreat, Alexius ceded the command to a high Albanian official named Comiscortes in the service of Byzantium. The city's garrison resisted until February 1082, when Dyrrachium was betrayed to the Normans by the Venetian and Amalfitan merchants who had settled there. The Normans were now free to penetrate into the hinterland; they took Ioannina and some minor cities in southwestern Macedonia and Thessaly before appearing at the gates of Thessalonica. Dissension among the high ranks coerced the Normans to retreat to Italy. They lost Dyrrachium, Valona, and Butrint in 1085, after the death of Robert.

Question: What fell to the Normans in the 10th century?

Answer: Robert Guiscard's conquests in the Balkans and the capture of Dyrrachium and Butrint in 1085 are the most significant events in the Normans' history. However, the Normans were not the first to capture the city of Dyrrachium, as the Venetians had secured a victory there in 1081. The Normans were also not the first to capture Butrint, as the Venetians had secured a victory there in 1081. The Normans were not the first to capture Valona, as the Venetians had secured a victory there in 1081. The Normans were not the first to capture Ioannina, as the Venetians had secured a victory there in 1081. The Normans were not the first to capture Thessalonica, as the Venetians had secured a victory there in 1081.

